  {
    "user": "U05UK5T7LPP",
    "type": "message",
    "ts": "1726197288.410409",
    "edited": {
      "user": "U05UK5T7LPP",
      "ts": "1726197397.000000"
    },
    "client_msg_id": "8887bda3-e0fd-44b2-aebf-8e7504b9d959",
    "text": "I would recommend David Ribes' work on this subject of (other) domain logics. Lately I have approached visualization design studies as a method of soliciting (as Konrad has it) discussions with collaborators that are more about 'time correlations' and less about 'FOOBAR program suite'.\n(ribes 2019) <https://dl.acm.org/doi/pdf/10.1145/3359140>\n(otto 2024) <https://osf.io/9f5ub>\n> The theory of boundary objects describes how designed artifacts support coordination between different expert stakeholders. [...] In contexts where technological mediation makes ‘seams’ between domains hard to traverse, visualization artifacts are valuable because they enable experts to share knowledge with other stakeholders.",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1726102208.402909",
    "parent_user_id": "U02U0AS3J49",
    "attachments": [
      {
        "from_url": "https://osf.io/9f5ub",
        "service_icon": "https://osf.io/favicon.ico",
        "id": 1,
        "original_url": "https://osf.io/9f5ub",
        "fallback": "Open Science Framework: 2024_BELIV_Boundary_Objects_Camera_Ready.pdf",
        "text": "Presented by OSF",
        "title": "2024_BELIV_Boundary_Objects_Camera_Ready.pdf",
        "title_link": "https://osf.io/9f5ub",
        "service_name": "Open Science Framework"
      }
    ],
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
